(214, NULL, 1, 42, 1, 1, 'Tribal Habitat', 'tribal-habitat', 'Tribal Habitat', 'Tribal Habitat', 'Tribal Habitat', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/tribalhaibat.jpg\" style=\"height:350px; width:850px\" />The house, universally plays an intermediary role between the human beings and their world. It is recognized as a powerful material cultural institution, and more apparent in the case of tribal populations. The tribal dwelling has a communicative significance of built form. It is generally built &ldquo;On a human scale by human skills for human needs&rdquo;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The tribal populations of India have varied models of subsistence. Some rely on hunting gathering and foraging state while some others follow nomadic mode of life including nomadic pastoralism and transhumance, yet still others practice rudimentary agriculture, including swidden cultivation and the peasantry life. The external environment and subsistence technology are the two major factors determine the character of tribal dwelling and the architecture.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The Tribal Habitat open air exhibition represents some of the tribal dwellings from different parts of the country. The selection of communities represented is based primarily upon to highlight the adaptive relationship of subsistence activity to its environment as well as some characteristics of the tribes. The exhibition also aims to highlight the simple but highly functional and efficient structures that the tribal communities construct using indigenously available material in the limited resources. These dwelling unit are not simply shelters or storages but vital cultural institutions around which the entire life-cycle of the people is woven.&nbsp;<br />\r\n			&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 1, 0, 'pTribal Habitat/p', '2024-12-10 03:27:06', '2025-04-08 04:28:41'),
(215, NULL, 1, 42, 1, 1, 'Coastal Village', 'coastal-village', 'Coastal Village', 'Coastal Village', 'Coastal Village', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Coastal Village-4 (2)_1738400860.jpg\" style=\"height:350px; width:850px\" />The rich cultural diversity of India&rsquo;s coastal communities can be experienced at the <em>Coastal Village</em> exhibition. Spread over 20 acres alongside the famous Upper Lake of the Bhopal city, this unique exhibition displays traditional house types and lifestyles from India&rsquo;s vast coastline habitat.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The lifesize exhibits include the <strong>Naalukettu and Arappura</strong> wooden houses from Kerala, built without iron nails, and <strong>Mirdhabari</strong>, the fishermen&rsquo;s abode from Odisha&rsquo;s Ganjam district. Visitors can explore a <strong>110-foot Snake Boat</strong> from Kerala, a <strong>Bhadrakali Ambalam Temple</strong>, and the <strong>Gudeessa</strong>, the traditional house of Andhra Pradesh fishermen. You&rsquo;ll also find a <strong>Fishermen&rsquo;s Settlement</strong> made of coconut leaves, offering a glimpse into coastal life. This exhibition invites visitors to immerse themselves into vibrant traditional architectures and cultures of the coastal regions.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 2, 0, 'pCoastal Villagenbsp/p', '2024-12-10 03:28:07', '2025-02-01 03:38:00'),
(216, NULL, 1, 42, 1, 1, 'Desert Village', 'desert-village', 'Desert Village', 'Desert Village', 'Desert Village', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Bunga.JPG\" style=\"height:350px; width:850px\" />The rich cultural heritage of India&rsquo;s desert regions can be experienced at the&nbsp;<em>Desert Village</em>&nbsp;exhibition. This open-air display proudly showcases the traditional houses of the Kutch region of Gujarat and Rajasthan, highlighting the livelihood of desert communities. Visitors can xplore the <strong>Rabari Houses</strong>, known for their stunning murals made of mud, sand, wood, and grass, along with vibrant embroidery using mirrors and colorful threads. The Rabaris&rsquo; intricate crafts bring life and color to the desert landscape. Adjacent is the <strong>Banni artisan community</strong> houses, and Rajasthan&rsquo;s <strong>Neem Ki Dhani</strong>, a mud and grass house built for the harsh desert environment. Also featured is the <strong>Haveli of the Paliwal community</strong> and a <strong>Cenotaph</strong>, beautifully carved from yellow sandstone in memory of ancestors. This exhibition captures the essence of desert life, blending resilience with artistic expression.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 3, 0, 'pDesert Village/p', '2024-12-10 03:28:38', '2025-04-09 04:21:40'),
(217, NULL, 1, 42, 1, 1, 'Himalayan Village', 'himalayan-village', 'Himalayan Village', 'Himalayan Village', 'Himalayan Village', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Himalyan Village_1738402015.JPG\" style=\"height:350px; width:850px\" />Step into the <em>Himalayan Village</em> exhibition, where the blend of unique architectural forms and rich cultural heritage come to life. Explore the <strong>Chaukhat</strong>, an imposing towering house, and the traditional <strong>Kothi</strong> from Himachal Pradesh, showcasing intricate stone and wooden architecture. Walk through the <strong>Parol</strong>, a traditional gate, and marvel at the <strong>Bhutia tribe&rsquo;s house</strong>, which reflects the lifestyle of this indigenous community. Discover the spiritual significance of the <strong>Manei</strong>, a huge prayer wheel, and experience the warmth of the <strong>Ladakhi kitchen</strong>, bringing a slice of Ladakh&rsquo;s mountain life to the plains.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>This open-air exhibition presents the architectural grandeur and the ingenuity of the communities living in the challenging mountain environments. The exhibition offers a glimpse into the traditional lifeways and architectural legacy of the communities living in the high Himalayan Mountains.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 4, 0, 'pHimalayan Village/p', '2024-12-10 03:30:49', '2025-02-01 03:57:28'),
(218, NULL, 1, 42, 1, 1, 'Mythological Trail', 'mythological-trail', 'Mythological Trail', 'Mythological Trail', 'Mythological Trail', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/updatedLillar kothi.jpg\" style=\"height:350px; width:850px\" />The Mythological Trail exhibition is a significant tribute to the folk and tribal myths of India. This open-air exhibition captures the essence of intangible traditions and translates them into tangible forms through traditional arts and crafts works. These myths, deeply tied to the cultural and spiritual life of the communities, have been meticulously brought to life by about 60 artists. They have crafted 42 exhibits using an array of materials, including clay, stone, brass, terracotta, iron, and paintings. The myths are depicted in two and three-dimensional forms, and the exhibits can be broadly classified into three categories- creation, sustenance, and destruction. The diversity of materials used in these creations highlights the ingenuity of the artists, who have employed their craftsmanship to preserve and communicate their rich cultural heritage. So far, the exhibition has created forty-two spaces dedicated to tribal and folk myths, rituals, and beliefs. The exhibition offers an insightful journey into the worldviews of the communities in India.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 5, 0, 'pMythological Trail/p', '2024-12-10 03:31:32', '2025-04-08 04:38:38');
