(219, NULL, 1, 42, 1, 1, 'River Valley Cultures', 'river-valley-cultures', 'River Valley Cultures', 'River Valley Cultures', 'River Valley Cultures', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/River valley cultures_1739600799.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The River Valley Culture Exhibition is planned to highlight the rich history, traditions, and lifestyles of civilizations that flourished along major river valleys of India. Exhibition will highlight the intricate relationships these cultures maintained with their river environments. Detailed reconstructions of various house types and community structures will offer a glimpse into daily life. At present there are two exhibits in this exhibition which not only educates about the significance of river valley civilizations but also fosters appreciation for their lasting contributions to modern society.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Narbadaji </strong>: Gond, Pardhan and Baiga adivasis living along the river Narmada, near the place of its origin tell numerous folk stories that reflect the cultural personality of the river that seems to be residing in the minds of the people since ages. They all lovingly call it as &#39;Narbada Mai. A few of the stories told by the villagers were recorded in an artist&#39;s camp organised by IGRMS. Stories presented in the exhibit were somewhat more popular and formed a basis of the art works created by the adivasi folks who used one or other part of the story as a theme. In narrations and expressions of the people, a natural variety exists that offer more than one basis for underlying frame work of unity. In the end it all gives a feelings that Narbadaji is not just a flowing volume of water. It is also a timeless, continuous flow of faith, an eternal belief and cultural investment into the forces of Nature.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p><strong>Dogra House: </strong>&nbsp;It is a traditional house type of the folk community &lsquo;Dogra&rsquo; of Jammu region with its cultural uniqueness and splendor. Dogra is a multi-caste community. Hindus, Sikhs and Muslims residing in this area share the common name Dogra. This house type is brought from village Piyan, situated in the remote hilly area of Akhnoor tehsil of Jammu.&nbsp; For the construction of houses, about seven to eight feet long square pillar &lsquo;Lina&rsquo; and circular pillar &lsquo;Tham&rsquo; are used. These pillars are arranged in four parallel rows of six pillars each. A distance of about six feet is kept between two pillars. Square pillars are erected in both the side and rear wall and circular pillars are erected in the verandah and inner chamber. These pillars are joined at the upper end by means of square wooden slabs, Kansari and Shisha to form the base for the roof. The roof is made from a thick layer of soil. The roof slopes backwards as wellas a wooden dtrain called parnala are attache to the either side of the roof which allows water to drain easily during the rainy season. These earthen roofs and walls provide protection to them in the adverse weather of snowfall. The walls, ceiling and floor are smeared with cow dung. The outer part of the walls is painted in black and white respectively.The boundary of the courtyard has been made from circular stones obtained from the local river.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 6, 0, 'pRiver Valley Cultures/p', '2024-12-10 03:33:45', '2025-02-15 00:56:52'),
(220, NULL, 1, 42, 1, 1, 'Traditional Technology Park', 'traditional-technology-park', 'Traditional Technology Park', 'Traditional Technology Park', 'Traditional Technology Park', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/updatedtraditionaltechnology.jpg\" style=\"height:350px; width:850px\" />The Traditional Technology Park is an open-air exhibition that delves into the creative brilliance of the technology and wisdom of the traditional past that thrive among the communities in India. This exhibition showcases 26 fascinating exhibits from across the country, each highlighting the practical, innovative solutions developed by communities to meet their basic needs in their livelihood and cultural environments.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Through these exhibits, visitors can discover the deep connection between traditional technologies and the foundations of modern advancements. It features, traditional time keeping devices, Water operated pounding mills and levers, mechanical pounding lever, oil expellers, irrigation system operated both with men and animal power, traditional threshing machine, Iron extracting and forging technology, salt-making, a technology for kneading mortar through lime, and wooden and iron gears used for crushing sugarcane for preparation of jiggery etc. The collections celebrate the knowledge passed down through generations, revealing how these age-old technologies continue to inspire the contemporary world.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>This exhibition is not only a tribute to the practical skills of the past but also a celebration of India&rsquo;s intangible heritage, offering a fresh perspective on the intersection of tradition and technology.<br />\r\n			&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 8, 0, 'pTraditional Technology Park/p', '2024-12-10 03:35:22', '2025-04-08 04:41:08'),
(221, NULL, 1, 42, 1, 1, 'Kumharpara', 'kumharpara', 'Kumharpara', 'Kumharpara', 'Kumharpara', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/updatedkhumarpara.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The&nbsp;Kumharpar Open-Air Exhibition, which opened on March 7, 2018, offers a unique opportunity to explore potter&#39;s creativity and craftsmanship from various parts of India. The unique handmade pottery practices of the the North-eastern India and Laddakh, pottery craft from the sand-dune painted potteries from Pokhran, Rajasthan and Gujarat, Kumar pottery of Majuli island of Brahmaputra, ceremonial pottery of Madhya Pradesh, terracotta arts of Odisha, West Bengal, and Tamilnadu are featured in the exhibition. A pottery tower of Manipur with a majestic mythical symbol of a deity used in Andro pottery of Manipur is also the major attraction of the exhibition.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The exhibition allows artisans to express their culture and share their indigenous wisdom. With 12 stunning exhibits sourced from different parts of India, visitors can witness the unique pottery traditions and their deep cultural significance behind each piece. The exhibition also invites you to engage directly with potters during museum workshops or during their annual renovation periods, offering rare opportunities to observe their techniques and learn about their craft firsthand.<em>&nbsp;Kumharpara</em>&nbsp;is more than just a display&mdash;it&#39;s an immersive experience that celebrates the legacy of pottery in India, connecting visitors to the heart of these creative traditions.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 9, 0, 'pKumharpara/p', '2024-12-10 03:36:02', '2025-04-08 04:31:40'),
(222, NULL, 1, 42, 1, 1, 'Sacred Grove Complexes', 'sacred-grove-complexes', 'Sacred Grove Complexes', 'Sacred Grove Complexes', 'Sacred Grove Complexes', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Sacred Grove-2_1739448131.JPG\" style=\"height:350px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Indira Gandhi Rashtriya Manav Sangrahalaya (IGRMS) is dedicated to preserving and celebrating India&#39;s ancient tradition of nature worship through the recreation of sacred groves&mdash;known as &quot;Gardens of Gods&quot;&mdash;in its campus. These groves, cherished by communities across the country, are not only natural sanctuaries but also carry immense cultural and spiritual significance. The museum has collaborated with communities to recreate eight sacred groves, each representing different parts of India: Devrai from Maharashtra, Kovil Kadu from Tamil Nadu, Umang Laigi Laikon from Manipur, Pavithra Vanam/Kaavu from Kerala, Maw-bu-Khar from Meghalaya, Oran from Rajasthan, and Sarna from Jharkhand and Chhattisgarh.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>These sacred groves embody the connection between nature and spirituality, where traditional rituals for appeasing deities and honoring ancestors are performed. Visitors may experience firsthand how these practices are kept alive through annual ceremonies and rituals. The groves serve not only to keep the museum campus green but also to educate visitors on the vital importance of conserving these cultural heritage sites. Join us to explore the tradition of sacred groves and witness how communities continue to nurture these sacred lands protected through rituals and ecological care. This exhibition is unique in this sense that rather displayed at one place it is spread in the whole campus for using the geographical characterstics of the museum premises.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 10, 0, 'pSacred Grove Complexes/p', '2024-12-10 03:36:40', '2025-02-13 06:32:32'),
(223, NULL, 1, 43, 1, 1, 'Veethi Sankul', 'veethisankul', 'Veethi Sankul', 'VeethiSankul', 'VeethiSankul', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/updatedVithi Sankul.JPG\" style=\"height:350px; width:850px\" />&#39;Veethi Sankul&#39;, literally translated as &#39;an assemblage of galleries&#39;, is a title addressed to the Indoor Museum of the Indira Gandhi Rashtriya Manav Sangrahalaya. Spanning 10,000 square meters under a dome-shaped architecture, it houses twelve galleries showcasing the diverse facets of human cultures. The entrance gallery, <em>Biocultural Evolution of Man</em>, traces humanity&#39;s evolutionary journey, with an additional section on <em>Human Variation</em>. The remaining galleries, grouped as <em>Human Odyssey</em>, highlight the rich cultural patterns of tribal and rural India through models, dioramas, panels, and ethnographic objects from India and abroad. A unique Visual Storage-cum-Research Gallery supports academic research, while an adjoining reference library offers an extensive collection of books and manuscripts. Veethi Sankul also features an amphitheatre and auditorium, a souvenir shop, a periodical gallery, wheelchair access, mothers corncers and Braille labels for visitors with special needs.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 1, 0, 'pVeethiSankul/p', '2024-12-10 03:40:02', '2025-04-08 04:22:41'),
(224, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Human Bio Cultural Evolution', 'human-bio-cultural-evolution', 'Human Bio Cultural Evolution', 'Human Bio Cultural Evolution', 'Human Bio Cultural Evolution', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Human Bio Cultural Evolution -1_1739601594.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The Human Bio-Cultural Evolution gallery traces the evolutionary journey of humans, starting with Earth&#39;s 4.5-billion-year geological timeline. Graphic panels illustrate key milestones, including bipedalism, cranial capacity growth, and manual dexterity. A highlight is the Narmada skull discovery, shedding light on human evolution in the Indian subcontinent. Dioramas depict prehistoric life, while exhibits on Stone Age cultures showcase tool development from the Palaeolithic to Neolithic periods. A dedicated section on human variation features a DNA model, offering scientific insights into the diversity of modern humans.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pHuman Bio Cultural Evolution/p', '2024-12-10 03:41:06', '2025-02-15 01:10:06'),
(225, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Human Odessey - Subistence Pattern of Livelihood', 'hospol', 'Human Odessey - Subistence Pattern of Livelihood', 'Human Odessey Subistence Pattern of Livelihood', 'Human Odessey Subistence Pattern of Livelihood', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Human Odessey- Subsistence pattern of Livelihood -3_1739602036.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The Saga of Human Destiny highlights the diversity of human cultures, their livelihood patterns and possession of material cultures exhibited by the simple and complex societies. The survival strategies of the communities living in different ecological settings are deeply entwined to their economic, religious and socio-cultural life. The gallery illustrates important aspects of the livelihood patterns, simple and complex societies ranging from the Hunter-gatherers Pastoral, Nomadic and Transhumant Communities, Shifting and Terrace cultivators, Peasant societies, Artisan communities, Migrant labourers and the gypsies.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pHuman Odessey Subistence Pattern of Livelihood/p', '2024-12-10 03:42:38', '2025-02-15 01:17:31'),
(226, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Mandwa Gohri - The Bhil and Rathwa Ritual Exhibits', 'mandawa', 'Mandwa Gohri - The Bhil and Rathwa Ritual Exhibits', 'Mandawa', 'Mandawa', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Mandwa Gohri- The Bhil and Rathwa Ritual Exhibits -9_1739602174.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The gallery presents collections from the Bhil and Rathwa tribe. Exhibits explaining the festival, social ceremonies, and ritual aspects important to the community are emphasized with aesthetic artworks such as clay-relief art, paintings, and objects. The depiction of Gohri Puja, Bhil, and Rathwa marriages (Mandava), Pabuji&#39;s Shrine, Ind Puja with objects, photographs, and artwork installations is one of the unique features of this gallery. This gallery&#39;s prized collection consists of around 40 black and white photographs captured in the mid-20th century A.D. by a renowned photographer Late Shri Anandi Lal Pareek.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pMandawa/p', '2024-12-10 03:43:34', '2025-02-15 01:19:51'),
(227, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Lingo Yatra - A Festival of the Koitor', 'lingo-jatra', 'Lingo Yatra - A Festival of the Koitor', 'Lingo-Jatra', 'Lingo-Jatra', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Lingo Yatra- A Festival of the  Koitor -1_1739602247.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The gallery celebrates the Lingo-jatra, one of the biggest festivals of the Gond tribe, showcasing the cultural richness of the Koitor people. It features photographs and material culture that immerse visitors in the festive ambiance. Central to the display is a cluster of clan flags, symbolizing the traditional concept of Bhum, the land of the Clan Gods. The gallery houses rare ritual objects, basketry, bell metal items, musical instruments, fishing tools, paintings, and woodcraft. Artefacts from the Ghotul, the Muria youth dormitory, provide deeper insights into the age-old institution of the community.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pLingo-Jatra/p', '2024-12-10 03:44:13', '2025-02-15 01:21:00'),
(228, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Ethnic Art', 'ethnic-art', 'Ethnic Art', 'Ethnic Art', 'Ethnic Art', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Ethnic Art-1_1739601333.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>This gallery provides an understanding of a variety of ethnic art forms of the tribal and folk communities. It offers a joyful experience of various sculptures, intricate wood carving, decorative marriage lamps, clay and lattice works, Gond and Australian aboriginal&rsquo;s painting, tattoo art of the Baiga tribe, traditional Madhubani Paintings, and the woodcrafts depicting the Dasavatara. A huge painting of an elephant by a Gond artist, paddy craft of the Bhottara tribe, Odisha are central to this gallery.&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pEthnic Art/p', '2024-12-10 03:45:06', '2025-02-15 01:05:56'),
(229, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Belief System, Cosmology and Rituals', 'cosmology-and-rituals', 'Belief System, Cosmology and Rituals', 'Cosmology and Rituals', 'Cosmology and Rituals', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Belief System, Cosmology and Rituals -1_1739602345.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>This gallery is centered around religious beliefs and practices within various communities. It explores myths and legends that transcend time and space, reflecting cosmic views beyond the sky and earth, delving into the deep concerns of the human mind and culture. Notable displays include <em>Hantakois</em>&mdash;wooden effigies symbolizing the Nicobarese belief in life after death&mdash;and Buddhist ritual artifacts like <em>Kapalas</em>, <em>Tangkha</em> paintings, and musical instruments used by monks. Intricately carved sacrificial pillars and wall paintings further highlight how cultures express their cosmic worldview through religious practices and beliefs.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pCosmology and Ritualsnbsp/p', '2024-12-10 03:46:01', '2025-02-15 01:22:37'),
(230, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Ethno-musical Gallery', 'ethno-musical-gallery', 'Ethno-musical Gallery', 'Ethno-musical Gallery', 'Ethno-musical Gallery', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Ethno-musical gallery -2_1739601269.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>This gallery invites visitors to explore an extensive collection of traditional musical instruments from across India. The exhibits are arranged typologically, offering a seamless journey through diverse forms of music-making. The collection includes idiophones, membranous drums, clappers, plucked instruments, and both wind and string devices. A standout feature is the massive <em>Pungjao</em> drum, created during a workshop in Manipur. Additionally, the gallery showcases the rare <em>Rawchem</em>, a unique wind instrument from the Mizo tribe, adding to the richness of India&#39;s musical heritage on display. A section is dedicated to the Indian Classical instruments. Rich collections of Banams, the string instruments of the Santal tribe are also featured in the gallery.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pEthno-musical Gallery/p', '2024-12-10 03:46:43', '2025-02-15 01:04:45'),
(231, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Masks', 'masks', 'Masks', 'Masks', 'Masks', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Masks -2_1739601415.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>This gallery showcases 187 masks from various Indian tribal groups and communities, featuring paper-m&acirc;ch&eacute;, wooden, and metal creations. Among the highlights are four life-size masks used in the&nbsp;by the Vaishnavs of Majuli Island, Assam. These bamboo-framed masks, covered with paper pulp, are hollow inside, allowing performers to animate mythical characters from the <em>Ramayana</em> or <em>Mahabharata</em>. The gallery categorizes masks into those used in performing arts, rituals, and tribal traditions, emphasizing their spiritual significance and the cultural narratives they embody.&nbsp;</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pMasks/p', '2024-12-10 03:47:41', '2025-02-15 01:07:17'),
(232, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Folk Cultures and Culinary Traditions', 'ethnic-cuisine-and-folk-art-traditio', 'Folk Cultures and Culinary Traditions', 'Folk Cultures and Culinary Traditions', 'Folk Cultures and Culinary Traditions', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Cultures of the Northeastern India -7_1739602595.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>This gallery offers a vibrant glimpse into the culinary traditions, featuring the kitchen cultures of the Chettiyar community and Nambudri Brahmins of Tamil Nadu and Kerala, and culinary artifacts from the Kutch, Gujarat. Visitors can explore an array of traditional kitchenware, from metal utensils to large wooden containers, spoons, pots, and stoneware. Additionally, the gallery showcases diverse artistic expressions, including intricate wood carving, beadwork, and traditional embroidery from across India. Ornately carved wooden pillars and grand dowry boxes stand as captivating highlights, reflecting the craftsmanship and cultural richness of these regions.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'Folk Cultures and Culinary Traditions', '2024-12-10 04:08:00', '2025-02-15 01:26:48'),
(233, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Cultures of the Northeastern India', 'cultures-of-the-northeastern-india', 'Cultures of the Northeastern India', 'Cultures of the Northeastern India', 'Cultures of the Northeastern India', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Cultures of the Northeastern India -4_1739602665.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>This gallery showcases 529 objects celebrating the vibrant cultures of Northeast India, representing all eight states of the region. A highlight is the Mythical World of Paphal collection from Manipur, part of the Museum&#39;s prestigious AA category i.e. object of national importance. A section is dedicated to the Neo-Vaishnava monastic traditions of Assam, alongside corners displaying artefacts from the tribes of Mizoram, Tripura, Meghalaya, and Arunachal Pradesh. Visitors can explore the Naga corner, which delves into the rich legacy of the Naga fertility cult through unique artworks and cultural items. The Sikkim corner features collections from the Lepcha, Bhutia, and Nepali communities, along with Buddhist monastic traditions.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pCultures of the Northeastern India/p', '2024-12-10 04:09:04', '2025-02-15 01:27:58'),
(234, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Visual Storage and Research Gallery', 'visual-storage-and-research-gallery', 'Visual Storage and Research Gallery', 'Visual Storage and Research Gallery', 'Visual Storage and Research Gallery', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Visual Storage and Research Gallery -2_1739602746.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>The Visual Storage Gallery serves a unique role by providing an overview of the Museum&#39;s diverse collections through selected samples of objects, and also facilitates study, research and exploration for scholars, academicians and the public. By offering visual storage, IGRMS broadens the scope of knowledge and supports ethnographic research, fostering academic engagement.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'Visual Storage and Research Gallerynbsp', '2024-12-10 04:10:27', '2025-02-15 01:32:23'),
(235, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Island Cultures of India', 'island-cultures-of-india', 'Island Cultures of India', 'Island Cultures of India', 'Island Cultures of India', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Island Cultures of India -1_1739603096.JPG\" style=\"height:370px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>This gallery highlights the rich cultures and traditions of India&rsquo;s islands, whether oceanic, river, lagoon, or lake-based. Showcasing a remarkable collection of photographs and ethnographic objects, it features river islands like Chilika, Srirangapatna, the Godavari, Kaveri, and Majuli on the mighty Brahmaputra in Assam. The gallery also presents rare artifacts and models from oceanic islands, including a special collection of a canoe from the Onge tribe of the Andaman Islands. Through these exhibits, visitors can explore the diverse lifestyles and traditions that thrive on India&#39;s unique islands.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pIsland Cultures of India/p', '2024-12-10 04:11:14', '2025-02-15 01:35:20'),
(236, NULL, 1, 43, 1, 1, 'Periodical Exhibitions', 'periodical-exhibitions', 'Periodical Exhibitions', 'Periodical Exhibitions', 'Periodical Exhibitions', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>Museum brings out Periodical Exhibitions at various instances on various themes from its collections. It offers other museums and institutions to venture short term exhibitions as a part of collaboration between institutional alliences, and programme of curation and exposition.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 3, 0, 'pPeriodical Exhibitions/p', '2024-12-10 04:13:23', '2025-01-30 00:23:18'),
(237, NULL, 1, 236, 1, 1, 'Exhibit of the Month', 'exhibit-of-the-month', 'Exhibit of the Month', 'Exhibit of the Month', 'Exhibit of the Month', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>The &quot;Exhibit of the Month&quot; series at IGRMS aims to present single-object exhibitions, providing visitors with in-depth information about a unique item from the museum&#39;s collection and its cultural significance. Each month, the curator unveils a selected object from the reserve collection at Veethi Sankul, the indoor museum building.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pExhibit of the Monthnbsp/p', '2024-12-10 04:14:12', '2025-01-07 02:36:55'),
(239, NULL, 1, 43, 1, 1, 'Online Exhibition', 'online-exhibition', 'Online Exhibition', 'Online Exhibition', 'Online Exhibition', '<p>Online Exhibition</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 4, 0, 'pOnline Exhibition/p', '2024-12-10 04:15:57', '2025-01-30 00:23:25'),
(240, NULL, 1, 239, 1, 1, 'Object of the Week', 'object-of-the-week', 'Object of the Week', 'Object of the Week', 'Object of the Week', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><em>&quot;Object of the Week&quot;</em>&nbsp;is a captivating virtual exhibition series that invites online visitors to explore the museum&#39;s collections. Every week, it showcases the museum&#39;s collections in a virtual format across various social media platforms, such as WhatsApp, Twitter, Facebook, Instagram, and on the IGRMS website.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pObject of the Week/p', '2024-12-10 04:16:56', '2024-12-13 04:51:55'),
(241, NULL, 1, 239, 1, 1, 'Online Periodical Exhibitions', 'online-periodical-exhibitions', 'Online Periodical Exhibitions', 'Online Periodical Exhibitions', 'Online Periodical Exhibitions', '<p>Online Periodical Exhibitions</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, NULL, 0, 'pOnline Periodical Exhibitions/p', '2024-12-10 04:17:43', '2024-12-10 04:17:43'),
