(293, NULL, 1, 42, 1, 1, 'Rock Art Heritage', 'rock-art-heritage', 'Rock Art Heritage', 'Rock Art Heritage', 'Rock Art Heritage', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Rock Art-4_1738400497.JPG\" style=\"height:350px; width:850px\" />Indira Gandhi Rashtriya Manav Sangrahalaya is the only museums in the world where original pre-historic rock paintings are found in the museum premises and developed in the form of an open-air exhibition named the Rock Art Heritage. There are 36 rock shelters containing Pre-historic painting situated in 4 locations in the museum premise. The Museum opened this exhibition in the year 1991. The rock art paintings ranges from Upper-palaeolithic period to Mesolithic Period and continued up to neolithic and historical periods. This Pre-historic site is geologically part of the ocean floor churned up in course of the upheaval caused by the clash of the central Indian and Tibetan tectonic plates. The paintings mainly depict hunting activities, vivid types of birds and animals, dancing peacock, women and men engaged in different activities, walking men and women sitting and standing positions, masked human figures etc. Most of the pictures are in several shades of red and white colors. The images of yellow colour found in rock shelter no. 15 and 23. Besides, there were approximately 75 human figures are found on the walls and ceilings of the shelter.&nbsp; The interesting fact in shelter no. 21 that&nbsp; human figures are inscribed in a group connected to each other in a dance posture. In the rock shelter 18, relatively large pictures of animals were drawn. The logo of IGRMS, a human image in walking posture is taken from one of these caves. An excavation was also conducted in one of the Rock Art Cave Shelter in the year 2000 A.D in which remarkable evidences were found from the Upper-palaeolithc period to neolithic periods; and also from historical periods. The Rock Art shelters of IGRMS believed to be the chain of Bhimbetka Rock Shelters.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 7, 0, 'pRock Art Heritage/p', '2024-12-13 03:38:27', '2025-02-01 03:32:03'),
(294, NULL, 1, 223, 1, 1, 'Koitor Yatra', 'koitor-yatra', 'Koitor Yatra', 'Koitor Yatra', 'Koitor Yatra', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>The gallery celebrates the Koitor Yatra, one of the biggest festivals of the Gond tribe, showcasing the cultural richness of the Koitor people. It features photographs and material culture that immerse visitors in the festive ambiance. Central to the display is a cluster of clan flags, symbolizing the traditional concept of <em>Bhum</em>, the land of the Clan Gods. The gallery houses rare ritual objects, basketry, bell metal items, musical instruments, fishing tools, paintings, and woodcraft. Artefacts from the <em>Ghotul</em>, the Muria youth dormitory, provide deeper insights into the age-old institution of the community.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 1, 4, NULL, 0, 'pKoitor Yatra/p', '2024-12-13 03:46:58', '2025-02-03 06:10:40'),
(295, NULL, 1, 355, 1, 1, 'Bhopal Gallery', 'bhopal-gallery-one', 'Bhopal Gallery', 'Bhopal Gallery', 'Bhopal Gallery', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://125.20.102.85/igrms/public/upload/files/Bhopal Gallery -4_1739601185.JPG\" style=\"height:350px; width:850px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Situated at the Avritti Bhavan towards lake side of the campus. The Bhopal Gallery is an exclusive exhibition showcasing the vivid history of the rulers of Bhopal from the 17th to the 20th century. This exhibition aims to introduce the historical monuments and heritage of Bhopal and delve into the associated memories. Historically, Bhopal was an integral part of the kingdom of Gonds, and the city still bears the remnants of this ancient kingdom. The reign of Nawabs and Begums spanned about 230 years before India&#39;s independence, marking an unparalleled fusion of Gondi, Parmari, Afghan-Pathan, Arabic, French, and English cultures with the local culture.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 2, 0, 'pBhopal Gallerynbsp/p', '2024-12-13 04:03:31', '2025-04-06 23:58:51'),
(297, NULL, 1, 41, 1, 1, 'Collection', 'collection', 'Collection', 'Collection', 'Collection', '<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>\r\n			<p>The IGRMS collects the traditional and contemporary cultural objects from folk and tribal people of India. It has a collection of more than 29000 ethnographic objects including some from other countries. The objects are mainly collected through field work by the curatorial officials exercise. The collection is categorised in 17 functional categories namely Agriculture, Animal Husbandry, Art and Craft, Basketry, Fishing, Games &amp; Amusement, Household, Hunting, Musical, Narcotics, Ornament, Ritual, Spinning &amp; Weaving, Textile, Tools, Travel &amp; Transport, Tools and Weapons.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', '', NULL, NULL, 3, 4, 3, 0, 'pCollection/p', '2024-12-21 04:11:12', '2025-02-10 07:02:25'),
